      "side": 1,
      "message": "From my understanding, the expected behavior of \"-gpu on\" is to create a sub-window on the host side, translate the GL commands and render to the sub-window. \"-gpu off\" will let the guest do software rendering and copy the framebuffer to the host. \"-gpu mesa\" shall behave the same as \"-gpu on\" except for the translator. But mesa does not create sub-window and instead sets up the gpu_frame_set_post_callback.",
      "parentUuid": "65984e34_67c0207d",
      "revId": "c79f50d73456980c780bcead054debedec06956d",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a567a60d_21f8d4a2",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 10,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2015-12-10T02:23:43Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "the sub-window is only useful when using host GPU drivers (-gpu on), because it will have its own desktop GL context and will be displayed on top of the UI window.\n\nFor \"-gpu guest\" and \"-gpu off\", we should display the framebuffer and not setup the GPU emulation libraries at all.\n\nFor \"-gpu mesa\", we should setup the GPU emulation library, but not create a sub-window. Instead, each frame is grabbed individually through glReadPixels() then displayed in the UI window directly (Mesa doesn\u0027t support native sub-windows, and it\u0027s faster anyway).\n\nFinally, there is now also \"-gpu swiftshader\" that should work exactly like \"-gpu mesa\" from this point of view.\n\nI\u0027m actually surprised you had to setup use_subwindow to 1 for mesa, it should be the other way !?!",
      "parentUuid": "6553ee27_35111a9d",
      "revId": "c79f50d73456980c780bcead054debedec06956d",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
